An '''informant''' or '''consultant''' in [[linguistics]] is a [[native speaker]] who acts as a linguistic reference for a language being studied. The informant's role is that of a senior interpreter, who demonstrates native [[pronunciation]], provides [[grammaticality]] judgments regarding linguistic [[well-formedness]], and may also explain cultural references and other important [[Context (language use)|contextual]] information to researchers from other cultures studying the language.<ref>{{cite book |first1= Paul |last1 = Newman |first2= Martha |last2 = Ratliff |title = Linguistic fieldwork |publisher = [[Cambridge University Press]] |year = 2001 |isbn = 978-0-521-66937-5 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=E_dDS6SenGsC&lpg=PA55&ots=upLUSbgEg7&lr=&pg=PA55#v=onepage&q=&f=false}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hr.uci.edu/uc-ser/b/15/aa2-06.html|title=Linguistic Informant|publisher=[[University of California, Irvine]]|accessdate=2009-12-21}}</ref>
